  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is there a database with all nutritional information?",
  "response": "There isn't a single, global database that contains all nutritional information, but there are several comprehensive databases and resources that are widely used for accessing nutritional information. Some of the most notable ones include:\n\n1. **United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) FoodData Central**: This is one of the most extensive and widely used databases available. It includes nutrient information on a vast array of foods, including branded and generic items. The database is continually updated and offers data on macronutrients, micronutrients, and other bioactive compounds.\n\n2. **European Food Information Resource (EuroFIR)**: This is a comprehensive network of food information databases concerning European foods. It provides access to a wide array of nutrient composition data across different countries in Europe.\n\n3. **Canadian Nutrient File (CNF)**: Managed by Health Canada, this database provides detailed nutritional information on foods commonly consumed in Canada.\n\n4. **National Food Database for Standard Reference (UK Nutritional Data)**: The UK government provides nutritional information through resources like the McCance and Widdowson\u2019s \"The Composition of Foods\", which is used for dietary assessments in the UK.\n\n5. **Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) Resources**: The FAO offers various resources and publications on food composition from around the world, including regional food composition tables.\n\n6. **Food Composition Databases from Other Countries**: Many countries have their own food composition databases, such as the Australian Food Composition Database or Japan\u2019s Standard Tables of Food Composition.\n\nThese databases are often available online and can be accessed freely or through subscriptions. They provide valuable information for researchers, dietitians, healthcare professionals, and consumers looking to understand the nutritional content of different foods.\n\nFor those interested in accessing a database, the USDA's FoodData Central is a good starting point as it is free and comprehensive. Other countries' databases may require language proficiency or specific access rights, depending on regional regulations and languages used.",
